<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="77" type="morphological data">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Morphological data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
This species keys to 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. jessicadimauroae" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" rank="species" species="jessicadimauroae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">A. jessicadimauroae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.130.1569" author="Sharkey, MJ" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" pagination="379 - 419" refId="B21" refString="Sharkey, MJ, Clutts, S, Tucker, EM, Janzen, D, Hallwachs, W, Dapkey, T, Smith, MA, 2011. Lytopylus Foerster (Hymenoptera: Braconidae: Agathidinae) species from Costa Rica, with an emphasis on specimens reared from caterpillars in Area de Conservacion Guanacaste. ZooKeys 130: 379 - 419, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.130.1569" title="Lytopylus Foerster (Hymenoptera: Braconidae: Agathidinae) species from Costa Rica, with an emphasis on specimens reared from caterpillars in Area de Conservacion Guanacaste." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.130.1569" volume="130" year="2011">Sharkey et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, but 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. nicklaphami" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" rank="species" species="nicklaphami">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">A. nicklaphami</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in many ways. Two of the most obvious are the wide sharply angled median propodeal areola and the sharp lateral longitudinal carinae on the first metasomal median tergite. In 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. jessicadimauroae" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" rank="species" species="jessicadimauroae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">A. jessicadimauroae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the areola is gradually narrowed anteriorly and the carinae are not sharp.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
This species can be morphologically distinguished from its nearest neighbor, 
<taxonomicName authority="Szépligeti, 1902" authorityName="Szépligeti" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Aerophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aerophilus colleenhitchcockae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colleenhitchcockae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Aerophilus colleenhitchcockae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by having the hind coxa and femur entirely brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Aerophilus nicklaphami, holotype." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.72197.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/619928" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">7</figureCitation>
) compared to mostly black (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.130.1569" author="Sharkey, MJ" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" pagination="379 - 419" refId="B21" refString="Sharkey, MJ, Clutts, S, Tucker, EM, Janzen, D, Hallwachs, W, Dapkey, T, Smith, MA, 2011. Lytopylus Foerster (Hymenoptera: Braconidae: Agathidinae) species from Costa Rica, with an emphasis on specimens reared from caterpillars in Area de Conservacion Guanacaste. ZooKeys 130: 379 - 419, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.130.1569" title="Lytopylus Foerster (Hymenoptera: Braconidae: Agathidinae) species from Costa Rica, with an emphasis on specimens reared from caterpillars in Area de Conservacion Guanacaste." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.130.1569" volume="130" year="2011">Sharkey et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
: figs 5, 6).
</paragraph>
